comments.text: Could they have fallen off the trail? Well, the answer to that is that it would in fact be very easy to fall off the Pianista trail from the beginning of the hike up to the Mirador. There are multiple locations where the incline is very steep and there is a steep drop to one side of the trail. This isn't a beginners level trail like many people seem to be saying online, just go watch someone hike the full trail with a go-pro to see for yourself. Is it likely in this case? No. If they had fallen off the trail they wouldn't have gotten far from it and would still be visible from the track. The direction of the trail would also have been evident to anyone who had fallen, once they came around, seeing as you just have to follow the incline. That being said, could someone have gotten lost in the area AFTER the Mirador? Absolutely. Most of that area is basically a trench where the path is clear, but there are pretty long stretches where the trench becomes a little ditch with multiple roads leading off the trail, either going into the forest and circling back towards the main trail or just ending abruptly. If you're really paying attention, you SHOULD be able to navigate your way thru this but that is assuming you are in good lighting conditions and you are not panicking/speed-walking the trail because you are afraid the sun will go down before you have enough time to get back. Unfortunately, I think that is exactly what happened to the girls on their way back up the Mirador. They made their way to the first stream and beyond, maybe even all the way to the paddocks where the cows graze. At some point they realized it was getting dark and turned back, and once they got back to the thick, flat forested area on the other side of the Mirador they realized just how dark it already was in the forest. They got anxious, as literally anyone in that position would, and they probably sped up. They really should have just spent the night on the trail at this point, but let's be honest... WHO here would actually do that? Literally all of us would be like 'fuck it, I'm not gonna be stranded in this jungle all night, let's go!' at least if we had the same level of experience as the girls, didn't have any equipment (specifically flashlights) or any kind of tent/external communication/way to defend oneself against whatever might cross you on that path at night. Keep in mind they were also both women in their early 20's, I can guarantee you they were absolutely panicking with the only thing in their mind being how fast they can get back to the lodge. Anyways, this is the point at which they left the trail, almost certainly. The trail is unmarked, or at least it was in 2014, and they eventually wandered too far away from it to find their way back. They didn't want to stay in one place so they wandered around the forest for a bit, probably eventually hearing a stream at which point they followed that to where it led them. Where that stream led them was down into the valley with multiple rivers that exists just East of the trail. They went further East only to have their path blocked off by a 10 foot waterfall, so they turned back West. They weren't about to go back into the dark forest they just came from so they decided to follow the river back to civilization, but that river kept going on and on and on. Eventually both girls where exhausted after days of walking. They came across a pretty steep decline that during the wet season is a set of cascading waterfalls but in early April is just a jumbled bunch of rocks you could potentially climb and jump down to the base. It wasn't from dehydration because they managed to survive at least 10 days from April 1st which would have been impossible with only the two or so bottles of water they packed. In addition to this, they probably both ended up suffering from hypothermia once their bodies could no longer produce enough heat. Their core body temps must have just gotten too low one of those nights and they either died of cardiac arrest or organ failure.
